properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Strong southeasterly winds of 70 to 90 km/h winds expected Tuesday. An approaching frontal system will spread very strong winds to Vancouver Island and the Sunshine Coast Tuesday. Winds will rise late Tuesday morning and persist into Tuesday evening. The strongest winds are expected over exposed coastal sections near the Strait of Georgia, Haro Strait, and the Southern Gulf Islands. Winds are expected to ease behind the frontal system Tuesday night. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of mixed winter weather expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: Eastern and southeastern Labrador, as well as the Upper Lake Melville area. Time span: Beginning Wednesday morning and lasting into the weekend. The end time is uncertain at this point. Details for Wednesday: Snow, ice pellets, freezing rain, and rain will affect southeastern Labrador and the Upper Lake Melville area. Snowfall amounts will range from 10 to 20 cm inland by Thursday morning, with rainfall amounts of 10 to 20 mm along the coast. A significant area of freezing rain is likely to occur inland as well. Details for Thursday to Sunday: All above mentioned forms of precipitation will continue through Thursday and likely Friday as well, with significant amounts of each. At this time, it looks as if conditions will begin to improve in some areas on Saturday, but may continue in other areas into Sunday. Further details will be provided in subsequent messages, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
